            "creation_date": 1399625799,
            "body": "<p>You have following options:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pass the File<\/strong><br>This means you can only process files. I wouldn't use this, unless you need the meta data (name, size, ...). Also, the file passed could be a directory, meaning additional checks.<\/li>\n<li><strong>Pass the data as byte array<\/strong><br>This requires a lot of effort to read the data first, and also doesn't scale well with larger data (all of it would have to be in the memory). Not recommended.<\/li>\n<li><strong>Pass an URL<\/strong><br>This is more flexible as the file variant, as it allows to pass file URLs (file.toURI().toURL()), resource URLs (Class.getResource(...)) and web URLs. The data is then read by opening an input stream from the URL. Recommended for any resources.<\/li>\n<li><strong>Pass the data as InputStream<\/strong><br>Very flexible, the input stream can be created from anything (also useful for testing, allows to create the test data from a String). Also efficient, allows streaming of data. Generally recommended. Hint: always wrap the passed <code>InputStream<\/code> into a <code>BufferedInputStream<\/code>, this greatly improves performance.<\/li>\n<li><strong>Pass the data as a Reader<\/strong><br>When reading character data, this is the recommended alternative to using an InputStream (where you would need to know the character encoding, or would need to pass it as an additional argument). Hint: always wrap the passed <code>Reader<\/code> into a <code>BufferedReader<\/code>, this greatly improves performance.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>If you write a reusable API, I recommend to provide following variants:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>void parseFile(URL url) // delegate to parseFile(Reader)\nvoid parseFile(InputStream in, String encoding) // delegate to parseFile(Reader)\nvoid parseFile(Reader reader) // parsing code\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 23560459,
            "question_id": 23559941
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5e29d2624e7e9a02320b3055a1d62193?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2415386,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2109526,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2109526/alex-suo",
                "reputation": 3167,
                "display_name": "Alex Suo",
                "accept_rate": 43
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1399624585,
            "creation_date": 1399624585,
            "body": "<p>I think the normal way is you pass the File object through and have 1 method creating and closing the streams.<\/p>\n\n<p>The File object is nothing but consider it a file descriptor which doesn't have any resources associated. Once you open the stream for a file, then there is the problem about who is responsible to close it. Normally we could follow \"who create the resource is in charge of destroying it\" that means the file stream opening and closing should really be in the same method. <\/p>\n\n<p>If you want to customize the parsing of the content, you should make the line parsing method abstract (given you talking about parsing I assume this is plain text file) or subclass that part. <\/p>\n\n<p>Having said all the above, if you are indeed doing text parsing, you should use BufferedReader which has both a lot of convenient methods like readLine() as well as better performance since it keeps a buffer internally, instead of going to the stream each time for a character.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 23560061,
            "question_id": 23559941
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cfe5f7d64f44be04f147295f5c7b88e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 71739,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 207421,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/207421/user207421",
                "reputation": 311890,
                "display_name": "user207421",
                "accept_rate": 82
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1399624656,
            "creation_date": 1399624656,
            "body": "<p>Just pass the file and let the parsing method read it as it needs to. Preloading it into a byte array just wastes time and space.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 23560092,
            "question_id": 23559941
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e77099e0dddc9e57f47c2c08e0c5404c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1677335,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1542547,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1542547/gabriel-ruiu",
                "reputation": 2823,
                "display_name": "Gabriel Ruiu",
                "accept_rate": 71
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1399625002,
            "creation_date": 1399625002,
            "body": "<p>My opinion is that there are <strong>two<\/strong> ways to think about this:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>inputting the File directly just saves time and is simple to understand<\/li>\n<li>providing a byte array as input allows more flexibility as to where the content comes from, as long as it is eventually transformed into a byte array, you could eventually have an external service that feeds the content from somewhere else<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>I would go for the <strong>second<\/strong> option, and as a suggestion give the <a href=\"http://mvnrepository.com/artifact/commons-io/commons-io/2.4\" rel=\"nofollow\">Apache Commons IO<\/a> library a try. It has a FileUtils and IOUtils class that provides some convenient methods for playing around with files and streams.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 23560213,
            "question_id": 23559941
        }
